3b. The t-statistic is our means of assessing whether a coefficient is statistically significant. We can calculate the t-statistic by dividing the coefficient by its standard error, as follows:

3/1.3
## [1] 2.307692

Since 2.3>1.96, we know that the coefficient lies above the 97.5th percentile, meaning that it is significant at the 95% level.

We can also calculate the exact percentile this estimate falls at:

#do coefficient estimate divided by standard deviation
pnorm(q=(3/1.3))
## [1] 0.9894919

98 is above the 97.5th percentile, so we have confirmed that this estimate is significant at the 95% level.

3c. There is less than a 5% chance that we would see a B1 value at least this far from 0 based on sampling variation alone (i.e., based on the assumption that the null hypothesis is true).

5d. Adding many polynomial powers to the model makes the model increasingly harder to interpret. Additionally, higher-order terms might make the model more complex without actually improving its fit. Lastly, there is also the risk of overfitting, in which your model becomes too highly responsive to the data, and maybe even begins to fit noise. When a model is too closely matched to the training data set, it will fail to generalize well when applied to other datasets.

6c. We cannot tell whether theres a statistically significant difference in hours worked between having 2 children and having 3 children under the age of 5 from this table. If we are assessing whether a categorical variable has a significant effect as a whole, we need to look at all the category coefficients rather than the individual coefficients. This is achieved through a joint F test, where you compare the predictive power of the model against a version where the categorical variable has been removed as a predictor.

  3. The pollsters could apply inverse sampling probability weights, which would allow them to accomodate for the different representations of demographic groups in their sample. By giving data points from each demographic group in the sample a weight proportionate to their prevalence in the population, the pollsters could re-weight their sample to represent each demographic group in proportion to its presence in the population.

Language-specific instructions:

  • We didnt cover easy summary statistics commands in the book. In R you can use summary() on the variable. In Stata try summarize and in Python, data['variablename'].describe().
summary(dengue$humid)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
 0.6714 10.0088 16.1433 16.7013 23.6184 30.2665       2

Humid ranges from 0.6714 to 30.2665, with a fairly normal distribution, given that the mean and median are about the same (16). Therefore, it makes sense that when humidity is zero, the likelihood of dengue is decreased by a significant factor (almost 50 % 0.416), because humidity is very rarely zero. It is most often around 16.

Calculate the residuals of that regression, and then make a plot that will let you evaluate whether there is likely heteroskedasticity in the model. Rerun the model with heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors. Show both models, and say whether you think there is heteroskedasticity

Language-specific instructions:

  • In both R and Python, save the model as m7, and m7b if you rerun with robust standard errors.

In R, use fiter(!is.na(dengue$humid)) on the data before running the model so the residuals line up properly. Use the msummary() function from the modelsummary package to display the results with the stars = TRUE option. Also, if youre clever about msummary() usage, you can skip creating m7b. You can access residuals using resid(m7).

In Stata, you can access residuals using predict resid, r after running the model.

In Python, use dengue.loc[~pd.isna(dengue['humid'])] on the data before running the model so the residuals line up properly. You can access residuals using m7.resid.

filtered_dengue <- dengue|> filter(!is.na(dengue$humid))
m7 <- lm(humid ~ temp, data = filtered_dengue)
msummary(m7, stars=c('*' = .1, '**' = .05, '***' = .01), output='regression_table_4.html')
resids <- resid(m7)
library(ggplot2)

First method: see how OLS predictions compare to actual values of Y across X

print(ggplot(filtered_dengue, aes(temp, humid)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm'))
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Second method: graph residuals explicitly across X

#create new empty df; add x (humid) and residuals into it
resid_data <- data.frame(filtered_dengue$temp, resids)
View(resid_data)
Warning in system2("/usr/bin/otool", c("-L", shQuote(DSO)), stdout = TRUE):

modules/R_de.so'' had status 1

Both graphs illustrate minimal heteroskedasticity, since the residual terms do not vary significantly across values of X. They do vary somewhat in magnitude (growing higher as X grows higher), but they do not vary significantly in sign (ie negative residuals at low value of X, positive residuals at high values of X).

We will also assess heteroskedasticity using the robust standard errors:

library(sandwich)
m7b <- msummary(m7,vcov = 'robust', stars=c('*' = .1, '**' = .05, '***' = .01), output='regression_table_5.html')
Warning in get_vcov.default(model, vcov = vcov, conf_level = conf_level, : The
`lmtest::coeftest` function does not seem to produce a valid result when applied
to a model of class lm. Only the standard errors have been adjusted, but p-
values and confidence intervals might not be correct.

The minimal heteroskedasticity is confirmed in comparing the coefficients in tables 4 and 5: since the coefficients do not change between the robust and non-robust versions of the model, we can assume minimal heteroskedasticity.

  1. Bonus challenge: figure out how I decided on a form where you log humidity and keep temperature linear.

As seen in the above graphs, the relationship between temperature and humidity (without logging), has a slight rightward skew with a few outliers close to low values of X (around -20). We know from Chapt 13 that one of the solutions to making a skewed relationship with outliers appear more linear is to log the outcome variable. Perhaps the author observed the shape of the relationship in question 7 and decided to try logging to mitigate the influence of outliers and address the rightward skew.
